<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Chapter 01: Tables vs Classes — SQL to C#</title>
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Outfit:wght@400;500;600;700;800&family=Source+Serif+4:wght@300;400;600&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
    <style>
        :root {
            --bg: #f8f7f3; --bg2: #f0ede6; --bg3: #e8e4db; --white: #ffffff;
            --ink: #1c1a17; --ink2: #3d3a34; --ink3: #6b6760; --ink4: #a8a49e;
            --rule: #dedad3;
            --acc: #c96b1e; --acc-l: #fdf3eb; --acc-b: #f5c99a;
            --green: #1d6b45; --green-l: #edf8f2; --green-b: #9fd9bc;
            --blue: #1a4f8a; --blue-l: #edf2fb; --blue-b: #afc8ef;
            --amber: #7a5200; --amber-l: #fdf8ec; --amber-b: #e8d08a;
        }
        * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
        html, body { font-family: 'Source Serif 4', serif; background: var(--bg); color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.6; }

        nav { position: sticky; top: 0; height: 54px; background: rgba(248,247,243,0.96); backdrop-filter: blur(12px); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); display: flex; align-items: center; padding: 0 2rem; z-index: 1000; }
        nav .nav-brand { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 12px; text-decoration: none; margin-right: auto; }
        nav .nav-brand-text { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-weight: 700; font-size: 18px; color: var(--acc); }
        nav .nav-pill { background: var(--acc-l); color: var(--acc); font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; padding: 4px 10px; border-radius: 12px; }
        nav .nav-link { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: var(--ink); text-decoration: none; }
        nav .nav-link:hover { color: var(--acc); }

        main { max-width: 960px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 60px 2rem; }
        .chapter-header { margin-bottom: 48px; }
        .chapter-label { font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink4); letter-spacing: 1px; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 12px; }
        h1 { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 42px; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
        .chapter-intro { font-size: 17px; color: var(--ink2); line-height: 1.7; max-width: 700px; }

        .section { margin-bottom: 56px; }
        .section-header { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
        .sec-num { font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 11px; color: var(--ink4); letter-spacing: 1px; }
        .sec-rule { flex: 1; height: 1px; background: var(--rule); }
        h2 { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 24px; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 12px; }

        /* Requirement box — the real-world scenario */
        .requirement {
            background: var(--amber-l); border: 1px solid var(--amber-b); border-radius: 8px;
            padding: 14px 18px; margin-bottom: 16px; font-size: 14px; color: var(--ink2); line-height: 1.6;
        }
        .requirement strong { color: var(--amber); font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 12px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; }

        /* Thinking boxes — how SQL dev vs C# dev approaches it */
        .thinking { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
        .think-sql, .think-csharp {
            border-radius: 8px; padding: 14px 16px; font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.6;
        }
        .think-sql { background: #1c1a17; color: #d4d0c8; }
        .think-sql strong { color: var(--acc-b); font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; display: block; margin-bottom: 6px; }
        .think-csharp { background: var(--blue-l); border: 1px solid var(--blue-b); color: var(--ink2); }
        .think-csharp strong { color: var(--blue); font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; display: block; margin-bottom: 6px; }

        /* Code comparison */
        .code-comparison { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
        .triple-comparison { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
        .code-block { border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.6; overflow-x: auto; }
        .code-block pre { margin: 0; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; }
        .sql-block { background: #1c1a17; color: #d4d0c8; }
        .csharp-block { background: var(--blue-l); border: 1px solid var(--blue-b); color: var(--ink); }
        .ef-block { background: var(--green-l); border: 1px solid var(--green-b); color: var(--ink); }
        .dapper-block { background: var(--amber-l); border: 1px solid var(--amber-b); color: var(--ink); }
        .code-label { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink4); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; margin-bottom: 6px; }
        .code-full { margin-bottom: 16px; }

        /* Mapping table */
        table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-bottom: 16px; background: var(--white); border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden; }
        thead { background: var(--bg2); }
        th { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-weight: 600; padding: 10px 14px; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); font-size: 12px; }
        td { padding: 8px 14px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--bg3); font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 12px; }
        td code { background: var(--bg); padding: 2px 5px; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 11px; }
        tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
        .sql-type { color: var(--amber); font-weight: 500; }
        .csharp-type { color: var(--blue); font-weight: 500; }

        /* Navigation */
        .chapter-nav { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 48px; }
        .nav-item { background: var(--white); border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; text-decoration: none; transition: all 0.2s; }
        .nav-item:hover { border-color: var(--acc); }
        .nav-item.prev { text-align: right; }
        .nav-item-label { font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 11px; color: var(--ink4); text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 4px; display: block; }
        .nav-item-title { font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink); }
        .nav-item:hover .nav-item-title { color: var(--acc); }

        footer { background: var(--bg2); border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); padding: 28px 2rem; text-align: center; color: var(--ink3); font-size: 13px; margin-top: 40px; }

        @media (max-width: 768px) {
            h1 { font-size: 32px; }
            .code-comparison, .thinking, .triple-comparison { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
            .chapter-nav { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
            .nav-item.prev { text-align: left; }
            main { padding: 40px 1.5rem; }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <nav>
        <a href="index.html" class="nav-brand">
            <span class="nav-brand-text">SQL to C#</span>
            <span class="nav-pill">CH 01</span>
        </a>
        <a href="index.html" class="nav-link">&larr; All Chapters</a>
    </nav>

    <main>
        <div class="chapter-header">
            <div class="chapter-label">Chapter 01</div>
            <h1>Tables vs Classes</h1>
            <p class="chapter-intro">You get a requirement: "Store customer data." A SQL developer thinks in tables and columns. A C# developer thinks in classes and properties. Both are solving the same problem — here's how to convert between them.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- 01: Store customer data -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">01</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>Requirement: "Store Customer Information"</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>Business Requirement</strong><br>
                We need to store customers with their name, email, age (optional), account balance, active status, and signup date.
            </div>

            <div class="thinking">
                <div class="think-sql">
                    <strong>SQL Developer Thinks</strong>
                    I need a table called Customers. Each piece of data is a column. I'll pick the right data types — NVARCHAR for text, INT for numbers, BIT for yes/no. Age is optional so I'll mark it NULL. I'll add an auto-incrementing primary key.
                </div>
                <div class="think-csharp">
                    <strong>C# Developer Thinks</strong>
                    I need a class called Customer. Each piece of data is a property. I'll pick the right types — string for text, int for numbers, bool for yes/no. Age is optional so I'll use int? (nullable). EF will handle the primary key.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-comparison">
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">SQL — Create the Table</div>
                    <div class="code-block sql-block">
                        <pre>CREATE TABLE Customers (
    Id        INT IDENTITY(1,1) PRIMARY KEY,
    Name      NVARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    Email     NVARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    Age       INT NULL,
    Balance   DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
    IsActive  BIT NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,
    CreatedAt DATETIME2 NOT NULL DEFAULT GETDATE()
);</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">C# — Create the Class</div>
                    <div class="code-block csharp-block">
                        <pre>public class Customer
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; } = "";
    public string Email { get; set; } = "";
    public int? Age { get; set; }
    public decimal Balance { get; set; }
    public bool IsActive { get; set; } = true;
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
}</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 02: Type mapping -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">02</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>How SQL Types Convert to C# Types</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>The Question</strong><br>
                I have a SQL column. What C# type should I use?
            </div>

            <table>
                <thead><tr><th>SQL Type</th><th>C# Type</th><th>When to Use</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">INT</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">int</span></td><td>IDs, counts, quantities</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">BIGINT</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">long</span></td><td>Large IDs, file sizes</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">BIT</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">bool</span></td><td>Flags: IsActive, IsDeleted</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">NVARCHAR(n)</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">string</span></td><td>Names, emails, text</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">NVARCHAR(MAX)</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">string</span></td><td>Descriptions, long text</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">DATETIME2</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">DateTime</span></td><td>Dates, timestamps</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">DATETIMEOFFSET</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">DateTimeOffset</span></td><td>Dates with timezone</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">DECIMAL(p,s)</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">decimal</span></td><td>Money, prices</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">FLOAT</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">double</span></td><td>Scientific, not money</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">UNIQUEIDENTIFIER</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">Guid</span></td><td>Distributed IDs</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><span class="sql-type">VARBINARY(MAX)</span></td><td><span class="csharp-type">byte[]</span></td><td>Files, images</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>

            <div class="thinking">
                <div class="think-sql">
                    <strong>SQL: Nullable = NULL keyword</strong>
                    If a column can be empty, mark it <code>NULL</code>. If it must have a value, mark it <code>NOT NULL</code>.
                </div>
                <div class="think-csharp">
                    <strong>C#: Nullable = ? suffix</strong>
                    If a property can be empty, add <code>?</code> after the type: <code>int?</code>, <code>string?</code>, <code>DateTime?</code>.
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 03: Protect the data -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">03</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>Requirement: "Protect the Data"</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>Business Requirement</strong><br>
                Email must be unique. Name is required. Age must be between 0 and 150. We need validation at both the database and application level.
            </div>

            <div class="thinking">
                <div class="think-sql">
                    <strong>SQL Developer Thinks</strong>
                    I'll add constraints: NOT NULL, UNIQUE, CHECK. The database will reject bad data no matter what — even if someone runs a manual SQL script.
                </div>
                <div class="think-csharp">
                    <strong>C# Developer Thinks</strong>
                    I'll add validation attributes: [Required], [MaxLength], [Range]. The app will catch bad data before it hits the database, with user-friendly error messages.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-comparison">
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">SQL — Constraints</div>
                    <div class="code-block sql-block">
                        <pre>CREATE TABLE Users (
    Id        INT IDENTITY(1,1) PRIMARY KEY,
    Email     NVARCHAR(255) NOT NULL UNIQUE,
    Name      NVARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    Age       INT NULL
              CHECK (Age >= 0 AND Age <= 150),
    CreatedAt DATETIME2 NOT NULL
              DEFAULT GETDATE()
);</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">C# — Data Annotations</div>
                    <div class="code-block csharp-block">
                        <pre>public class User
{
    public int Id { get; set; }

    [Required, EmailAddress, MaxLength(255)]
    public string Email { get; set; } = "";

    [Required, MaxLength(100)]
    public string Name { get; set; } = "";

    [Range(0, 150)]
    public int? Age { get; set; }

    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
}</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <table>
                <thead><tr><th>SQL Constraint</th><th>C# Annotation</th><th>EF Fluent API</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td><code>NOT NULL</code></td><td><code>[Required]</code></td><td><code>.IsRequired()</code></td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>PRIMARY KEY</code></td><td><code>[Key]</code></td><td><code>.HasKey()</code></td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>UNIQUE</code></td><td>&mdash;</td><td><code>.HasIndex().IsUnique()</code></td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>FOREIGN KEY</code></td><td><code>[ForeignKey]</code></td><td><code>.HasForeignKey()</code></td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>CHECK</code></td><td><code>[Range]</code></td><td><code>.HasCheckConstraint()</code></td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>DEFAULT</code></td><td>&mdash;</td><td><code>.HasDefaultValue()</code></td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Column width</td><td><code>[MaxLength]</code></td><td><code>.HasMaxLength()</code></td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>

            <div class="code-full">
                <div class="code-label">C# — Same thing with Fluent API</div>
                <div class="code-block ef-block">
                    <pre>modelBuilder.Entity&lt;User&gt;(e =&gt;
{
    e.HasKey(u =&gt; u.Id);
    e.Property(u =&gt; u.Email).IsRequired().HasMaxLength(255);
    e.HasIndex(u =&gt; u.Email).IsUnique();
    e.Property(u =&gt; u.Name).IsRequired().HasMaxLength(100);
    e.HasCheckConstraint("CK_User_Age", "[Age] >= 0 AND [Age] <= 150");
    e.Property(u =&gt; u.CreatedAt).HasDefaultValueSql("GETDATE()");
});</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 04: Auto-generate IDs -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">04</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>Requirement: "Each Record Needs a Unique ID"</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>Business Requirement</strong><br>
                Every order needs a unique ID. For our main app, sequential numbers are fine. For our distributed microservice, we need IDs that can be generated without talking to the database.
            </div>

            <div class="thinking">
                <div class="think-sql">
                    <strong>SQL Developer Thinks</strong>
                    Sequential: use IDENTITY(1,1) — the database auto-increments. Distributed: use UNIQUEIDENTIFIER with NEWSEQUENTIALID() to keep index performance.
                </div>
                <div class="think-csharp">
                    <strong>C# Developer Thinks</strong>
                    Sequential: just name the property "Id" and EF handles it. Distributed: use Guid and generate it client-side with Guid.NewGuid().
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-comparison">
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">SQL — Auto-Increment</div>
                    <div class="code-block sql-block">
                        <pre>-- Sequential (most apps)
CREATE TABLE Orders (
    Id    INT IDENTITY(1,1) PRIMARY KEY,
    Total DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL
);

-- Distributed (microservices)
CREATE TABLE Events (
    Id   UNIQUEIDENTIFIER PRIMARY KEY
         DEFAULT NEWSEQUENTIALID(),
    Type NVARCHAR(50) NOT NULL
);</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">C# — EF Handles It</div>
                    <div class="code-block csharp-block">
                        <pre>// Sequential — EF auto-detects "Id"
public class Order
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public decimal Total { get; set; }
}

// Distributed — generate client-side
public class Event
{
    public Guid Id { get; set; } = Guid.NewGuid();
    public string Type { get; set; } = "";
}</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 05: Full example -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">05</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>Requirement: "Build a Product Catalog"</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>Business Requirement</strong><br>
                Store products with name, SKU (unique), price (must be positive), stock count, category reference, active flag, description (optional), and creation date.
            </div>

            <div class="thinking">
                <div class="think-sql">
                    <strong>SQL Developer Thinks</strong>
                    Products table → FOREIGN KEY to Categories → UNIQUE on SKU → CHECK on Price >= 0 → DEFAULT for stock and active flag → NVARCHAR(MAX) for optional description.
                </div>
                <div class="think-csharp">
                    <strong>C# Developer Thinks</strong>
                    Product class → navigation property to Category → Data annotations for validation → nullable string? for optional description → EF configures the rest.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-full">
                <div class="code-label">SQL</div>
                <div class="code-block sql-block">
                    <pre>CREATE TABLE Products (
    Id          INT IDENTITY(1,1) PRIMARY KEY,
    Name        NVARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,
    Sku         NVARCHAR(50) NOT NULL UNIQUE,
    Price       DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL CHECK (Price >= 0),
    Stock       INT NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
    CategoryId  INT NOT NULL REFERENCES Categories(Id),
    IsActive    BIT NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,
    CreatedAt   DATETIME2 NOT NULL DEFAULT GETDATE(),
    Description NVARCHAR(MAX) NULL
);</pre>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-full">
                <div class="code-label">C# — Entity</div>
                <div class="code-block csharp-block">
                    <pre>public class Product
{
    public int Id { get; set; }

    [Required, MaxLength(200)]
    public string Name { get; set; } = "";

    [Required, MaxLength(50)]
    public string Sku { get; set; } = "";

    [Range(0, double.MaxValue)]
    public decimal Price { get; set; }

    public int Stock { get; set; }
    public int CategoryId { get; set; }
    public bool IsActive { get; set; } = true;
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
    public string? Description { get; set; }

    // Navigation — the actual Category object
    public Category Category { get; set; } = null!;
}</pre>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-full">
                <div class="code-label">C# — EF Fluent API Configuration</div>
                <div class="code-block ef-block">
                    <pre>modelBuilder.Entity&lt;Product&gt;(e =&gt;
{
    e.HasKey(p =&gt; p.Id);
    e.Property(p =&gt; p.Name).IsRequired().HasMaxLength(200);
    e.Property(p =&gt; p.Sku).IsRequired().HasMaxLength(50);
    e.HasIndex(p =&gt; p.Sku).IsUnique();
    e.HasCheckConstraint("CK_Product_Price", "[Price] >= 0");
    e.Property(p =&gt; p.Stock).HasDefaultValue(0);
    e.Property(p =&gt; p.IsActive).HasDefaultValue(true);
    e.Property(p =&gt; p.CreatedAt).HasDefaultValueSql("GETDATE()");
    e.HasOne(p =&gt; p.Category)
     .WithMany(c =&gt; c.Products)
     .HasForeignKey(p =&gt; p.CategoryId);
});</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 06: Query preview -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">06</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>Requirement: "Find Expensive Electronics"</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>Business Requirement</strong><br>
                Show me all electronics products over $50, sorted by price (highest first). I just need the name and price.
            </div>

            <div class="thinking">
                <div class="think-sql">
                    <strong>SQL Developer Thinks</strong>
                    SELECT Name, Price FROM Products WHERE CategoryId = 3 AND Price > 50 ORDER BY Price DESC. Simple query with a filter and sort.
                </div>
                <div class="think-csharp">
                    <strong>C# Developer Thinks</strong>
                    Filter with .Where(), sort with .OrderByDescending(), project with .Select(). Use AsNoTracking() since this is read-only. Two syntax options: method chain or query syntax.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="triple-comparison">
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">SQL</div>
                    <div class="code-block sql-block">
                        <pre>SELECT Name, Price
FROM Products
WHERE CategoryId = 3
  AND Price > 50
ORDER BY Price DESC;</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">LINQ — Method Syntax</div>
                    <div class="code-block csharp-block">
                        <pre>var products = await db.Products
    .AsNoTracking()
    .Where(p =&gt; p.CategoryId == 3
             &amp;&amp; p.Price &gt; 50)
    .OrderByDescending(p =&gt; p.Price)
    .Select(p =&gt; new { p.Name, p.Price })
    .ToListAsync(ct);</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">LINQ — Query Syntax</div>
                    <div class="code-block csharp-block">
                        <pre>var products = await (
    from p in db.Products.AsNoTracking()
    where p.CategoryId == 3
       &amp;&amp; p.Price &gt; 50
    orderby p.Price descending
    select new { p.Name, p.Price }
).ToListAsync(ct);</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-full">
                <div class="code-label">Dapper — Direct SQL</div>
                <div class="code-block dapper-block">
                    <pre>await using var conn = new SqlConnection(connectionString);
var products = await conn.QueryAsync&lt;ProductDto&gt;(
    @"SELECT Name, Price
      FROM Products
      WHERE CategoryId = @CatId AND Price > @MinPrice
      ORDER BY Price DESC",
    new { CatId = 3, MinPrice = 50m });</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 07: Create indexes -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="sec-num">07</span><div class="sec-rule"></div></div>
            <h2>Requirement: "Make Searches Faster"</h2>

            <div class="requirement">
                <strong>Business Requirement</strong><br>
                Product search by name is slow. SKU lookups must be fast. We often filter by category + price together.
            </div>

            <div class="code-comparison">
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">SQL — CREATE INDEX</div>
                    <div class="code-block sql-block">
                        <pre>-- Speed up name search
CREATE INDEX IX_Products_Name
    ON Products (Name);

-- SKU must be unique + fast
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX IX_Products_Sku
    ON Products (Sku);

-- Composite: category + price together
CREATE INDEX IX_Products_Cat_Price
    ON Products (CategoryId, Price DESC);

-- Only index active products
CREATE INDEX IX_Products_Active
    ON Products (Name)
    WHERE IsActive = 1;</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="code-label">C# — EF Fluent API</div>
                    <div class="code-block ef-block">
                        <pre>modelBuilder.Entity&lt;Product&gt;(e =&gt;
{
    // Speed up name search
    e.HasIndex(p =&gt; p.Name);

    // SKU must be unique + fast
    e.HasIndex(p =&gt; p.Sku).IsUnique();

    // Composite: category + price
    e.HasIndex(p =&gt; new { p.CategoryId, p.Price })
     .IsDescending(false, true);

    // Only index active products
    e.HasIndex(p =&gt; p.Name)
     .HasFilter("[IsActive] = 1");
});</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

